Implements Claude Code's `PostToolUse` hook mode — the entry point that, after every Read/Edit/Grep/Glob, injects the not-yet-seen prefix of a file's `.ctx` chain into the agent's context as `additionalContext`.

The core invariant (owner-mandated): `run` never errors and never blocks the tool call. Every failure path — bad JSON, no path field, path outside repo, chain lookup error — degrades to either an empty string (emit nothing) or a `(ctx-context: chain unavailable for {rel}: {e})` marker payload, never a panic or hard failure. Malformed input silently produces `String::new()`.

Key behaviors an editor should know: `rel_target` strips the `base` prefix from absolute paths and rejects anything under `.context` or `.git` (the scaffolding itself must not get injected as context). `target_of` accepts either `file_path` (Read/Edit) or `path` (Grep/Glob) from the tool's parameters — whichever is present. `event_cwd` extracts the harness-supplied `cwd` from the raw event JSON independently of `HookInput`, so the caller can pick the correct `base` before invoking `run`; this is a separate parse pass over the same input string. Session deduplication defaults to `"default"` when `session_id` is absent.

Depends on `serve::fresh_chain_for` (session-scoped, stateful — tracks what's already been served) and `serve::render` for the injected text format; changes to the chain data model or render format must stay compatible with `serve.rs`. Uses `Env` trait abstraction (from `crate::env`) rather than touching the filesystem/session state directly, for testability.